review.itemreviewed: Fresh Foam X 1080 v14 Running Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: I’ve been wearing New Balance shoes for over three decades (including 1080s that I loved) and I’ve never encountered a heel counter design like these.  The back of the shoe tilts towards the toe and binds on the back of my heel bone.  Moreover, the heel liner material is grippy and not smooth, so your sock/foot won’t slide, adding to the friction. review.itemreviewed: Sawtooth X Low Waterproof Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: The Sawtooth X Low is more if a traditional hiking shoe and very robust in its style and materials used. Overall this pair a bit stiff and still trying to break them in. This means they are a little uncomfortable unlike other hiking shoes I have used in the past. Overall the shoes are a true-to-size so don't think you need to half size up or down.
review.name: Very stiff but supportive

review.itemreviewed: Sawtooth X Low Waterproof Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: I have only ever owned Oboz casual shoes and thought I would give their hiker a try. I was pleased to find the same supportive and cushioned insole (same as my Oboz Bozeman) and found that the shoe fit similarly too. I have a wider-than-average foot with a narrow heel and fit the Sawtooth X perfectly. Walking around the first thing that struck me was how comfortable they were out of the box. I didn't feel like I needed to break them in at all! I also love that the rubber on the bottom is nice and grippy. I look forward to putting many more miles on them.
review.name: Comfy, light and easy to break-in

review.itemreviewed: Sawtooth X Low Waterproof Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: During Covid I walked over 5,000 miles. I tried Salomon's, On's , Merrill's and others. I developed Achilles tendinitis and have picks OBOZ with orthotics as my go to show for my next 5,000 +++ miles. Size is perfect and true for me.
review.name: The only hiking shoe brand I'll buy

review.itemreviewed: Sawtooth X Low Waterproof Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody:
the length is just fine, but the shoe itself is sssssssssooooooooooo narrow
that my foot barely fits in.
review.name: Sawtooth X Low Waterproof Shoe - Men's

review.itemreviewed: Sawtooth X Low Waterproof Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody:
Made the mistake of ordering these in my same size as previous Sawtooths and found they are about a half-size larger than those. 

While these seem like they would be even more comfortable than the previous generation and offer a wider toebox in the medium width, I ultimately opted not order a half-size smaller because I wasn't wowed with the design of the tongue – which had the waterproof liner/gusset about a half-inch to three-quarters of inch from the top set of eyelets – thus making for a sizable amount of real estate for water incursion into the shoe, even when wearing a pair of pants. 

The older Sawtooths had the liner and gusset up to the top eyelets, which is the optimal design for water protection. To me, this is a serious shortfall in Oboz' design, but especially when they supposedly spent so long designing this new iteration...pretty daft on their part. They also had shoelaces that are very short and incapable of doing a knot on them, if you're like me and inclined to use a single-overhand or double-knot.
review.name: Runs larger than previous version

review.reviewBody: This thing came recommended by a friend and I tried his and it was pretty nice. For some reason the one I got is less flexible than a 2x4. Super cable-y and it pig tails really badly no matter how many times I pulled it through and flaked it. Stiff catch, difficult to give a good belay. Not a good rope for sport climbing because of how stiff the catches tend to be and how difficult it is with the pig tails. Love the thinness, weight and the durable feel but it really wasn’t worth the $$$ seeing as I nor anyone I climb with wants to use it! Maybe I just got a lemon or something but my buddy had a similar issue so 🤷🏻‍♂️
review.name: Not worth the $$$

review.reviewBody: I've used this as my main rope for 10s of thousands of feet of whipping and jugging. Over the course of this time it has received some fuzzy spots, BUT the core is perfectly intact. It's taken half a year of abuse and still looks new after a wash. Best rope ever. I find myself bringing it over other peoples ropes every time for the piece of mind when jugging and whipping on less than smooth rock. Can't reccomend it enough,
review.name: Future of rope technology

review.reviewBody:
This rope is the absolute best rope I've ever owned, period. If you're looking for a rope to do it all, this is it!

From speed climbing on bigwalls in Yosemite to Kyrgyzstan's remote alpine bigwalls, this rope has performed the best of all the ropes I've owned/used. 

It truly feels bomber, feeds (and catches!) in a grigri like a charm, handles great and it's relatively tangle free with a little care. I'm mostly amazed at its durability while free climbing, taking gnarly whips on it or jugging it as a fixed line on bigwalls, I just can't wear it out. 

8.9 is the smallest diameter I would go for an all around, and I honestly felt a bit spooked to use such a skinny rope for every type of climbing, but Edelrid found the perfect recipe and it just works! It also makes for a perfect alpine rope where weight matters and cut resistance is key.

When it's time to retire it, I'm 100% getting the same one again.
review.name: The absolute best rope I've ever owned

review.reviewBody: This 8.9 has become my daily driver and I'll never look back.  The aramid fibers add just the right amount of structure to a skinny rope for a perfect balance of supple handling and control.  The added cut resistance from the aramid fibers also gives me a huge peace of mind.  My only wish is that it came in a bi-pattern option.
review.name: New daily driver

review.reviewBody:
This cord is amazing.  

Skinny, yet durable.  The aramid weave in the sheath adds a lot of protection and makes this rope roughly as durable as any 9.8mm, but without the weight.  

Packs down to roughly the same size as a 50m, 9.8mm cord - and is especially light feeling on route.  

The handling is super nice, soft, and with a great hand feel.  The aramid gives the rope a really nice look and feel. 

Took it out into Little Cottonwood  for some pitches and put it to  full use with a wandering pitch of roofs where the rope had to run and rub across the edges. Held up like a champ.

At first look, you may do what i did, and go "Woah, this thing is skinny" - but after a few pitches on the rock, I am sold.  My partner and I both took a few small falls and didn't notice the difference in elongation and felt like the rope provided soft catches regardless.

I will update this review the more that I climb on it - especially if I take it into the alpine. More to come!
review.name: 8.9mm is the new 10mm.

name: Swift Protect Pro 8.9mm Dry Rope

review.reviewBody: These are hands down my favorite ice-climbing tools, and I get to play with many options because I run the @iceclimbing feeds on social media. review.itemreviewed: Circadia Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: Hello, I’ve read a lot of opinions about these shoes, especially the negative ones. I own the Circadia Low, which I mainly wear in the city and for everyday use. They are great for all regular surfaces. Although they aren’t particularly fashionable, they are perfect for my feet. When winter came, I was bothered by the draft on my ankles in the low shoes. So, I decided to buy the Keen Circadia Mid, mainly for comfort in the city during the colder months. When I took them out of the box, they were quite stiff, and after my first walk, they were uncomfortable around my ankles. Now I realize this was due to how they were stored in the box. I placed a jar inside them overnight and tied the laces. The next day, I was able to put them on comfortably and walk without any issues. I should also mention that I wore one pair of thin socks and on top of that, woolen socks for hiking boots. The socks make a big difference. The shoes are of good quality and will please anyone looking for shoes with plenty of room for toes.

review.itemreviewed: First Tracks Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Men's
review.reviewBody: Things that could make it better: Thumb Loops/thin stretchy material at the end of the sleeves, like they have with the first tracks down jacket. Maybe a loop or hole near the neck gaiter area to store sunglasses when not on your face (one of the drawbacks of all pieces with the neck gaiter style). The front chest pocket ripstop is kinda loud (?) when brushed against. Not a huge deal just an inference. Things I love: the warmth, it's surprisingly warm. Pair it with a waterproof shell and you should be good in most places. The fit (subjective), I am usually in between sizes and sized up - it fits exactly how I expect/want, I'd say true to size. I actually like the small hood, also subjective, but this will stay on my head without a helmet for just wearing casually which is what I wear it for. Probably too small for wearing with a helmet if riding. And a couple really cool features that I never knew I needed: The adjustable cinch at the bottom of the piece allows you to taper/close the bottom towards the hips. One issue I have with 99% of every fleece I've had is the fabric kinda "floats out" towards this hip area when wearing, and makes you look larger than you actually are. This is a great solution for that, so it makes fits quite a bit better with this cinch feature. Another is the pocket-ception, the secret stash pocket within the kangaroo pocket is a sneaky place to store small items. Who doesn't love a good stash pocket? Love the print, something other than just one color. I've been wearing it the last few days and want to wear it all the time, it's extremely comfortable. I imagine I will be grabbing this piece more often than most others in my closet this winter. Very happy with this purchase.
review.name: Really nice piece, some nice functional features and very versatile for all kinds of environments

review.itemreviewed: First Tracks Fleece Pullover Hoodie - Men's
review.reviewBody:
Basically a cargo fleece without looking like it, great layering and external piece. I am 5'6" 155lbs and with most items am right between a Small and Medium. With this item, I tried them both on, and they both fit. I went with the small as I'm planning on using this as a mid layer sometimes and for this item I wanted a slimmer fit, but if I was always going to wear it only as an outer layer, the medium's boxier/baggier fit would have worked fine. 

The hood's shape definitely makes it feel like there's a decent amount of material near/around my neck when I'm not wearing it up. Maybe that would've been a little less restrictive in the Medium, but the mesh lined hood and the added chin coverage were great when the wind and rain and hail picked up the other day. 

There are a couple great features that aren't listed in the description that are worth calling out. For starters, in the kangaroo pocket there is an internal mesh pocket almost the full width of the kangaroo pouch with its own top-access zipper, very nice as hoody pockets are typically useless for keeping items in. There is also an added keyring or bungee cord sorta thing inside the pocket, but I've been getting a kick out of keeping my keys on display on the external D ring - What a fashion statement. 

I like that this can be worn as a comfy hoody but has as much secure storage as many jackets with much more obvious/bulky looking pockets. 

This'll be a staple in my snowboard kit this winter and be great from going straight from the car into my storm shell.
review.name: True SM-edium, could go either way

It's a great layer for lounging around in or supporting you on and adventure. It works well on it's own or as a layering piece under a shell or jacket. It look nice enough to for casual things around town too.

review.reviewBody:
The waist belt is oversized. Especially when overheating is an issue with high volume activity like biking. Every excess covering of the skin reduces your cooling process. A 2” strap is all that is required for a 20L pack and could be removable for added convenience. 
 That type of sliding anchor point do fail in my experience when stressed which is unacceptable. They pop off. It’s probably more important than the hip belt for stabilizing your load. 
 The rear ventilation system is fair. From my experience a physical raise channel along the spinal column is superior. Having absolutely nothing touching your spine will enhance your cooling process. I own 2 packs that do this. It is possible. The rest is meh standard stuff. Nothing that will make you fall in love

review.reviewBody:
I finally decided on buying an an avalanche backpack for snowmobiling and touring adventures. After trying a few different ones, I decided on the BD Jet force pro. I thought at the time I liked the opsrey Soelden better but the JF Pro sat real well on my back and didn't move around. I also bought the 10 liter expansion. It's easy to change between 35 liter and 10 liter, making it easy to tailor to whatever adventure you might be going on.

I'm 5'9, 205 and the S/M fits me great. The avalanche bladder is super simple to repack. The battery powered system makes it easy to travel with as well as practice with. 

I highly recommend the BD Jet force Pro for anyone looking for an avalanche pack.

review.reviewBody: After much research, I decided this was the most dependable pack for the money. I purchased the 35 L and the 10L booster. I think 25L is ample for most tours, but I occasionally pack camera equipment, hence the 35. I've only needed to test deploy, but otherwise, the pack is no heavier than my non-avy pack and very comfortable. Some suggestions: I am a medium-build woman (5'9", 150 pounds), and even I would like the S/M to be a little smaller in the frame. I think it might be too big for the smallest of tourers. The 35L booster doesn't have enough adjustability; when it's not full, it flops around. This makes the 25L necessary for some tours. I would also love for this pack to allow for A-frame ski carry, which would necessitate changing the deploy of the bag I imagine. A larger hip pocket for more snacks would also be ideal.
review.name: Solid pack with a few suggestions

review.reviewBody:
Used this a a number of backcountry tours, from easy trees to steep couloir climbs. Best electric bag out there, hands down. All the features you could want, adjustable size, user friendly, and time-tested. Best part is the weight of the battery/fan is centered low on your back so feels much lighter than it is, compared to other brands that have it high/mid back and very top heavy when carrying. Stop debating and buy it.

Only recommendation would be to have some sort of low-profile cinch strap on the bottom half of the main compartment to help compress the bag when less full as the top straps squeeze everything to bottom and pooch it out.

review.reviewBody: I was looking for a smallish,sturdy  clamshell-style carry-on to use as a ski boot bag, because I had destroyed one and another was too heavy when fully packed. I like to carry my boots and essential gear with me ( thermals, ski pants, base layer, ski top, socks, ski mitts. liners, balaclava, goggles and sunglasses) after learning the hard way that if the airline loses your skis and/or luggage, it costs so much more time and $$  to replace all those items than it is to rent only skis, helmet and borrow or buy a jacket. This bag has a complete, zipped nylon partition that keeps the boots separated from the soft goods, is perfectly compact (smaller than a 22" carry on) which is important for little planes with limited overhead compartment size. And this bag is a stiffened soft-side, so is lightweight but does not crush. I LOVE this bag!  Now need one for regular travel.  5 + stars!!
review.name: Really great carry on!

review.reviewBody: Great looking carry on bag, with enough compartments, I have a backpack since 2013 and still look like new.
review.name: Awesome!

review.reviewBody: This is a really nice suitcase that is designed to hold a lot.  I have not used it for a trip yet but can tell it is going to well loved.  It rolls very well in any direction!

review.reviewBody: I was looking for a carry-on that would meet my need for functionality, followed by aesthetics.  Functionally, this bag has all the bells and whistles I was looking for. I love how the bag rolls easily and it meets the carryon size criteria for most domestic (US) airlines.  I was pleasantly surprised that even though the bag is considered "soft-sided" there is actually a good deal of exterior protection underneath the fabric and the bottom of the carryon is more of a hardshell in nature.  This pairs well with my Crossover 2 boarding bag! =)
review.name: Well Thought Out

review.reviewBody: As a frequent traveler I needed something durable and spacious.  The outer case and protective pockets put my mind at ease whether I am throwing the bag in the over head bin or checking it.  The inside of the bag allows me to pack shoes and outerwear separate from my dress clothes so I arrive with things still nicely folded and ready to wear.  You can easily fit a weeks worth of clothes in this carry on.

review.reviewBody:
This jacket fits great, keeps me warm and acts as a great mid/external layer. The pockets, design, fit and style all suit me well. I love that I can tuck away the hood and it sort of has a popped color. The color is a true red with some very small hints of a neon green that you have to find, so not terribly distracting.

I have to knock this down a star for the egregious labeling Helly Hansen has committed. There are FOUR logos spread through the chest and collar:
1) H/H on the Collar
2) H/H on the Shoulder
3) H/H on the sleeve by the elbow (you can't even see this in the photos)
4) "Helly Hansen" on the Inner lining, upper portion of the main zipper (so near your mouth)

1 -3 can be fixed with some black gore-tex sticky patches pretty easily.

Don't forget this is made by HELLY HANSEN
review.name: Solid jacket with obnoxious branding

review.reviewBody: So far, I really like this jacket, which I bought to replace an old REI jacket that I’d had forever. It doesn’t really get very cold during the winter here in Portland, OR, but it is consistently damp, so it’s nice to find a jacket that’s water repellent and not too warm. So far, it has worked well. I’d prefer if the logos were less prominent and if it were maybe an inch or so longer.
review.name: Just what I was looking for

review.reviewBody: I haven't used it yet still in box but will for the winter on deck....
review.name: Camp stove

review.reviewBody: The CampStove 2+ is the most important item in my survival kitchen department. It is an excellant and quick way to start a fire and boil water. It is fun to use. I have watched many videos about it but nobody stresses its strongest point. No matter how long the power is out; days, weeks, or months, you will never be without a phone and communication if you have a Biolite campstove. I have and love several other stoves, but this is the ONLY one that keeps my phone charged, night or day, rain or shine. If i can start a fire then i can communicate, only hecause of Biolite. I think every home should have one, maybe two.
review.name: Number One Survival Stove

review.reviewBody: Works like a dream. Came with high quality storage bags. Perfect gift for a touring motorcycle enthusiast.
review.name: Perfect gift for Touring Bike Motorcyclist.

review.reviewBody:
Biolite stuff is really great unless you actually use it. I’ve had 4x 330 headlamps fail within a few months. My Biolite stove battery stopped charging almost right away. 

I just bought a headlamp 330 and it doesn’t hold a charge. I wouldn’t want to be out in the middle of nowhere with their stuff. It’ll probably fail. poor quality control for their Chinese manufacturing.
review.name: Support has to be great for bad quality

review.reviewBody: I bought this stove and use it for the first time. I have been using various brand of reputable wood stoves. Yes, like most reviewers, the stove need lot of practice to start up. Also most scary part is the electric module kinda overheat and the fan automatically turn up the highest without any adjustments. I quick tear down the stove and put out all the hot ashes. So that the electricity module can cook down. I couldn’t off it and put falr away from my camp for fear of explosion…
review.name: The stove control module overheat
comment: Thank you for sharing your review. We would love to schedule some time to learn more about how you have been using the stove and offer some pointers. The power module should not overheat - especially if you're loading the stove properly. Please reach out to us at support@bioliteenergy.com and a member of our support team will schedule a call with you. We want to make sure you have a camping stove that you love!

review.reviewBody: I purchased this as a backup system to heat water and cook with maybe charge a phone. I have pulled it out 3-4 time per year to fire it up and make sure it works. I tried this year and the battery is flat as a pancake and is not charging via USB. I picked up a new battery thinking that was the issue but that one is not working either. I suspect the charging circuit is failing. I would love to buy a new CS2 v9 or later board to get it working again but no parts are around.
review.name: Great wen it works - need spare parts
comment: Thank you for the feedback and we're sorry to hear your Campstove is no longer accepting a charge. To help get you a working product, please reach out to our support team at support@bioliteenergy.com. We'd love to troubleshoot this issue with you and make sure you have a working product.

review.reviewBody: This was a gift to my husband and he loves it! Can’t wait to try it in the backcountry but we tested it at home and loved it.
review.name: Perfect gift

review.reviewBody: Firstly this thing is durable, ive given it a beating, caught it on fire, overheated it a couple times (dont recommend) but its still kicking and functions exactly the same. The only real downsides to this device is 1. It doesnt charge quite as fast as i would like given most devices have 4k mah batteries now, which is around double what the capacity was for phones when this stove was originally released. And 2 its slightly on the heavy side for backpacking. I would like to if anything, see a larger version working on the same principles for homesteading.
review.name: A life saver with a couple small catches

review.reviewBody: If I charge my mobile phone when I make a fire, the power generated will not maintain its normal operation, and it is not enough to charge the mobile phone device when the stove is fully charged.
review.name: Cannot charge my phone very well
comment: Thanks so much for the feedback. We are sorry to hear that you've had a subpar charging experience. The Thermo-Electric generator provides approximately 3 Watts of power while the stove is burning fuels. However, the USB output is capable of supplying more than 3 Watts. Devices with high power demands, such as the latest phone, would attempt to draw as much power as possible. This means the battery state of charge may gradually decrease over time, even when a fire is burning. Nevertheless, the battery depletion rate will be much slower compared to not having a fire at all.

review.reviewBody:
I was in between an 9 and a 10 but have slightly long fingers. 10 worked well if I didn't wear an additional fabric liner glove. Not overly big on my hand. With the extra liner (burton polartec) the 10s were too tight. Going to try an 11. 

Also my wrists are a little thin. I wish the velcro ran a little longer so I could tighten the wrist more. Not a big deal though. May have to add some more velcro on the wrists to the 11s.
review.name: Note on sizing

review.reviewBody: I needed a new pair of mittens or gloves. I researched and decided to buy the Fall Line mittens based on reviews and the sale price. I’ve only used a few days so far. First they are soft and fit well immediately. They are not like Kinco gloves which are stiff. Second they were pretty warm for the 30 degree days.  I've decided I do prefer mittens for warmth and can’t wait to use this winter.

CAUTION: BABE MAGNET

review.reviewBody: This is a great canoe for short day trips, multi-day relatively smooth river trips or flat water ponds and lakes. It is very sturdy, high quality and purpose built for fishing and adventuring. It tracks straight and is very maneuverable. I've taken it through a patch of class 2 rapids with confidence and it handled very well. I've also sat on still ponds and laid back to watch the sunset - with confidence. I am very happy with my purchase and I would recommend this canoe to anyone looking for a solo adventure vessel.

review.reviewBody: Have has been my solo for 3 years now it has been everywhere from big lakes to divert rapids. It sets nicely on the top of my jeep all summer long and gets used every weekend. Perfect for fishing of just paddling out.

review.reviewBody: For some strange reason I love wearing ski jackets as normal town jackets and I think this jacket deserves a place in my wardrobe. Here are my findings and toughts: 1.- It serves good for a layering system. I have worn a base layer or t-shirt then a hoodie a puffy jacket and then this jacket on top confortably with no restrictions for those extreme winter days. I'm 5-8" 180 lbs wearing an L size. 2.- It has better coverage than town jackets. The high neck hood covers you up to your lips and if you tilt your head a little it almost covers your nose so you get to breath the warm air coming from your body. Also the neck is confortable to your skin. When you have the hood down the high neck reaches your chin so it protects all your neck from the cold air. The sleeves have the same long lenght as any other SKI jacket from Patagonia or Eddie Bauer so in case you dont have gloves you can cover most part of your hands with the long sleeves. The overall length of the jacket is good for my size (5-8"). Not too long to interfere my legs and long enought to cover my rear and genitals. The buttons on the snow skirt are easy to button and separate. So you can button the snow skirt to prevent cold air to come up inside your jacket toghether with the hem adjustment. 3.- Pockets: the two front pockets are fleece lined and confortable, the chest pocket is an okay size for a regular cell phone. 4.- Vents: Altought Im not a very fan of mesh vents I havent felt the difference in breathability compared to non-meshed vents. I have worn this jacket in the spring showers (warmer weahter) with the vents open and the front zipper open (just the front velcros closing the jacket enough to prevent the rain to come in and all the air to pass thru the front and pit vents) and I didnt overheat at all. Not sure if it will work this way in a real downpur but at least light to moderate rain will do using the velcros only. 5.-DryVent Shell: so far the jacket feels very windproof and very waterproof and is not too hard or noisy when wearing. 6.-Overall feel: Its an easy jacket to wear and confortable. I havent use it to actually ski but it has everything a skier would need and it has a great range of movement in the arms. The only thing I dont like about the jacket is the white North Face logo (which is in the front and the back). I bought the black jacket and the logo can be seen like five blocks away. I prefer more subtle logos like Patagonia or Eddie Bauer but this is just me.
review.name: Great versatile jacket.

review.reviewBody: I purchased the jacket from Backcountry and the order never arrived. I received the purchase confirmation and after about a week of waiting checked back to see why the delivery was sent. My order number was no longer available and after talking to the customer service agent found out that they never completed my order. There was no communication about the cancelation, and if I did not reach out it would not have been noticed. They offered to repurchase the product, but of course, they no longer had it in stock. review.reviewBody: I really wanted to love these. I owned multiple pairs of the prior version, the x ultra 3, and the 4 is far from comparable. I lost treads on my first hike. A few weeks in I also lost my first toenail because the shoe allows your foot to slide no matter the tightness. The tongue does not stay straight so you get lots of little rocks in the shoe. The quality was poor and the shoes wore out in 3 months where I could get 6-12 out of the ultra 3. I am rough on my hiking shoes logging ~40mi a week with each hike averaging 2k elevation change, 2-4 hours trail time on the rocky mountains of the SW and I the 3's were the only shoe that could keep up... incredibly disappointing the drop in quality. I'm not sure why they made these changes but really hope by the time they put out an x ultra 5 that they go back to the prior materials.

review.itemreviewed: Traveler Spinning Rod + Case + Sock - 3 Piece
Traveler Spinning Rod + Case + Sock - 3 Piece
review.reviewBody:
I like this rod, I don't love it. It is too lightweight and far too specialized for a travel rod, and it isn't quite as nice as my other TFO rods. 
Part of this is due to mislabeling - I thought this was the TRV S 703-3 model, but it turns out this is the Lightweight version of TFO's travel series (the 702-3).  This particular rod would be a good (albeit expensive) lightweight trout or panfish rod. It is fairly long for a trout rod at 7' long though - I could see this being a strong candidate for canoe fishing in trout-heavy waters. 
I used this rod for two weeks of smallmouth fishing off of a boat and in a canoe on the Georgian Bay in Canada, mostly tossing Ned rigs and Texas-rigged crawfish. It lacked the backbone to do topwater lures.  The rod casts well and the extra length let me get some good distance with 1/10 oz jigheads. The tip is sensitive, and I had no issues feeling when a fish was hitting. 
I landed a little over 60 fish with this rod, so it's been through the ringer. I had it paired with an expensive 2500-sized reel, which was well balanced. The rod struggled mightily against 3 lb smallmouth, so if you're planning to use this for larger fish (or as a saltwater rod), I would look elsewhere. 
I would advise Backcountry.com to sell the heavier model of this rod (the Medium TRV S 705-3) as it'll be a lot more versatile than this particular one.  
One minor gripe: the dots meant to line up each section of the rod - they didn't line up. 
All in all, this is a good rod (especially for a 3-piece), but of the five travel rods I own, this won't be the one I point all of my friends toward purchasing.
review.name: Expensive lightweight rod

review.reviewBody: I got this for my 2022 Sonata. Among all the trunk-mount bike racks I've seen, this was the most expensive, but that's because it's the only bike rack I've seen that attaches with only 2 cables and is lockable. This is my first trunk-mount, so I have nothing to compare to, but this was a very easy installation. I can't imagine having 6 straps to deal with; I can figure it out, but it would probably annoy me and wouldn't look very nice (if that's what you care about). The hooks that attach to the trunk are gentle to the paint. Once installed properly, there's no play. Of course, make sure it's a confirmed fit for your car. When I tried to make it budge, it shook the car. The quick-release bike mounting bars are very secure when tightened. I have a mountain bike that would otherwise stick its back tire out to the left or right of the car if not for the ability to position the mounting bars off-center. It's very lightweight compared to a hitch and hitch-mount rack, so your rear suspension will thank you. Overall, definitely worth what I paid.
review.name: Snug Fit, Easy Install

review.reviewBody: We drove from NJ to VA without a problem. I would recommend this bike rack to those without a hitch.
review.name: Great Bike Rack

review.reviewBody: This thing is awesome. Looks great. Fits perfectly. Very secure. I wanted a hitch bike rack until I realized how not-straightforward it is to install a hitch. I assumed a car rack would de facto feel inferior but that’s not the case here.
review.name: Awesome. Will make you rethink needing a hitch.

review.reviewBody: Used to have raceway pro 3 bike rack, and once saw this newly designed bike rack how easy it can be installed, lock bikes, transport. Then bought it, used for fatbike, road bike, and simply just love it, it is such a ease to install on car, load bikes, securely lock bikes. Love it very much.
review.name: Light, Strong, and easy to install

review.reviewBody: So far this seems like a pretty sturdy and pretty well designed back rack (although the tire rim protector pads will be immediately lost if you forget to close the straps after removing a bike) BUT, although the Thule website says this rack fits a ‘22 Subaru Forester, nowhere does it say that the empty rack is not compatible with a Subaru automatic tailgate- the tailgate apparently senses the rack’s weight and the tailgate closes automatically and there doesn’t seem to be a way to keep the tailgate open other than holding it up. And the tailgate-mounted top strap clips don’t completely clear the body of the vehicle when the tailgate opens, so immediately begin to scuff and eventually I suppose bare metal will be exposed and the clips subject to rust(?) I would have considered a tow hitch-mounted rack if it had been clear ahead of time that this rack makes hands free access to the rear cargo area impossible. Calling Thule and Subaru about this didn’t produce conclusive results either, frustratingly.
review.name: Apparently not compatible with auto-tailgate
comment:
Thank you for sharing your feedback on the Thule Outway bike rack. 
Thule does not recommend operating an automatic tailgate with any bike racks attached to the vehicle. This is listed in a document in the Instructions section of the Thule.com product page, and is included with the bike rack. Sudden and unstoppable movement of the rear door could cause damage. Please contact the vehicle manufacturer for information on how to disable this feature as needed.

review.reviewBody:
Excellent quality, a few gripes. 

The side pockets are difficult to access when it is stuffed full, and with no belt pockets it turns every water/food break into a packs off thing. I plan to replace the belt with one with pockets to get some snack access. 

Additionally, mine did not come with a horizontal strap around the top 3rd like pictured (it does not even have the attachment loops for that strap on the back side of the pack… without that horizontal strap carrying rope is messy. 

The straps for crampons on the front worked fine for hiking in/out but during our summit push I found them too finicky and would just drop them into the bag to save time. 

I still rate it highly because it feels like with some mods I can make it work and it will work for quite a while. Really feels like the perfect size for the cascades.
review.name: High quality but a few gripes.

review.reviewBody:
This pack is certainly high quality. It feels great and wears nice. I used it last weekend on Mt.Shucksan in Washington state and it was just enough room for gear for one night. 

I'm not used to a minimalist pack and expect that I can resolve many of my gripes with some more experience and changing my systems a little bit. For one,  I struggled with the lack of accessible pockets without taking the pack off. Additionally the side pockets are hard to access while it is fully loaded making eating/drinking a pack off stop every time.

The tool attachments work fine for axes, but left my picket hanging low enough to scrape and smack into rocks on the scramble down the Fischer chimneys. The loops to secure the axe handles also seems to loosen over time. The front straps for crampon attachment did fine enough on the approach, but I found them too finicky to mess with during transitions.... they are just long enough to get around the crampons... but it is a tight fit....so ended up just tossing my crampons into the bag during the actual climb to save time. 

One thing that seems to be missing even on an ultralight pack are side straps to secure a rope. There is room to drape one on top of the bag, and the center strap over the top is big enough to secure over a rope... but without the side straps it got a little messy. 

Overall I am impressed with the quality, fit, style, and potential of the bag enough to recommend it... I expect I will get some slide on pouches for the waist belt though and maybe try to add straps to secure a rope.
review.name: Solid pack... some gripes.

review.reviewBody:
I was a product tester for this pack and used it extensively across the globe for more than a year before production. 

At first touch you can feel the quality. The fabric is certainly waterproof which is the main staple of this pack. It has some nice convenient pockets on each side with waterproof zippers. Great for snacks and such. Removable straps help synch the pack tight and hold a pair of crampons on the outside. It also works great with those straps removed for folks looking for a stripped down style. 

The bag is extremely light. Highly abrasion resistant. Unlikely to puncture or tear. And it keeps out everything from water to dust. If you manage to make it come apart then respect to you because I couldn’t!!

I used this bag ice climbing in Alaska, climbing in the Cascades, climbing in the Himalaya, and it’s become my go-to pack for travel where you will do an array of things from airplanes to jeeps to dusty trail. It’s just a really great bag that you will be super happy with. 

10/10. IMO this is THE pack.
review.name: Favorite pack ever!

review.reviewBody:
I had the previous Sirana in Size S. I bought the new version in size M. I am 31" waist. I think my waistline sits between the sizes. The old S I really liked but the length between waist and legs was quite small and I felt it made the legs ride quite high up. New version in M feels a bit too big. It is safe but when I close the buckle, even with the free floating webbing innovation that they have introduced, it doesn't sit amazingly. That being said it does feel comfortable overall. 
Major revisions:
1: the waist buckle is now much larger than previous version which I don't like as much. 
2: The structure is a bit more rigid in general. The previous model packed so small and collapsed easier into a crag bag.
3: new gear loops are just uncoated plastic. The loops sit very far forward on me and it can be annoying sometimes when I am trying to make take something off to place a piece on the wall as it is not the best location for my body. Would S have been better? I just followed the Edelrid size guide so am a bit confused!
4: The inner lining is totally seamless and feels very nice on the body.
5: The belay loop is very soft and collapses. The previous version had a rigid loop which was great for slapping a HMS Biner onto with one hand. The soft structure of the new harness means that a biner doesn't snap across it as easily.
6: The red color is nice but you have to accept TC has his signature on it ffs. I mean, whatever, its a harness right.

Chose this over nearest competitor (BD Solution) because of that 4th loop and the multi pitch potential of that. Plus Bluesign materials which feels nice for the soul.

Careful with sizing is all I can really say in summary.
review.name: Huge updates from previous version

review.reviewBody: You get what you pay for, what else can I say? These are very comfortable, warm, and give good ski control. Worst part is the price, but honestly they are worth it and feel very well-made. I have no doubts they will last for years. They run just a little bit small. I would recommend sizing up if you’re in between sizes. I wear a US men’s 11.5 and fit in a 46 comfortably.
review.name: Terrific boots

review.reviewBody: I bought them a month ago and wore them on a week long backcountry trip. No blisters, no cold feet and fell in love with them. Worn them almost everyday since then.
review.name: Fit, comfort and warmth no finer boot

review.reviewBody: I love these boots so much. I’ve always worn Alpina’s and this is my third pair and my favorite. They are stiff and provide great control but super-comfy straight out of box. No zippers or velcro either!
review.name: Best boots I’ve owned!

review.reviewBody: I haven't skied in these yet, but have been walking around the house in them and may be able to help with sizing. I wear a size 10/43 in virtually every kind of footwear, but the Alpina chart says a US men's 10 is a 44 in their boots, and it is, especially if you have forefeet on the wide side. I could get into the size 43, but there was noticeable pressure on my little toes, despite the rest of the boot feeling pretty good, so maybe if you have a narrower size 10 foot, the 43 will work. The 44 fits surprisingly snug in the well-shaped, well padded heel pocket, which is good, and has ample toe room up front. Also, unlike the Fisher Transnordic, the Alpina boots break smoothly across the top of my feet without a sharp crease when I flex it. I'll update this review if anything turns up after skiing them.
review.name: Sizing info

review.reviewBody:
I am a size 10.5 and had a hard time deciding what size would be best, given I'm taking these to the North Pole and will have thick and possibly double socks. 
I went with size 44, and was a perfect fit. There is still a pinch of room at the front of the toe yet the boot is snug around the top and sides of the foot.
10.5 = 44 I can promise you that.

I'll try to post a video / photo after visiting the arctic.
review.name: Perfect Fit, Excellent Boot, Ships Fast

review.reviewBody: I absolutely love these boots.  They're a total game changer for me on ungroomed trails and moderate backcountry touring.  My old Fischer boots were like wearing a pair of slippers, and I felt like I had zero control with them.  With these Alpina Alaska boots, my feet are comfortable, my ankles are supported, and I have great control on my skis.  I'm so happy I bought these, and I'm really grateful to Backcountry's customer service for helping me with some questions before I bought them.  For reference, I wear a women's 8-8.5, Euro size 39, and the 39 in this fits great.  I also tried the 40, but it was absolutely HUGE.  For me, these run true to size.
review.name: Best Cross Country Boot I've Ever Had!

review.reviewBody:
I'm a woman's US 7.5-8.0 in boots and ordered these in size 39. Although the box and the printed size on the back of the boot itself said 39, the sewn-in tag on the inside of the boot said EU38. Not sure what's going on there but since they felt a tad small (toes grazing the front when walking) I assume the inside tag was correct. Although I think I would have preferred true 39's, I decided to keep them as I was running out of time for a Christmas Day ski. But beware when you receive them to check the size on the back of the boot against the interior tag if they're not feeling like the correct size.

Aside from that, awesome boot. They kept my feet dry and WARM for over six hours including some walking through deep snow to get around fallen trees. For the first time ever, I didn't get blisters (silk sock liner + thin wool sock). They weren't as comfortable when walking as when on the skis, but again, possibly because of being the wrong size. I'm hoping the interior liner gets a little less cushy with time and will give my toes more room. All the metal ringlets and eyelets give a lot of options for different lacing techniques which also helped adjust them for more comfort than usual xc boots. 

They're expensive but worth it.
review.name: Size Discrepency
comment: Stephanie, I have a size 39. Used once.  They are too big for me.  Any chance, you want to trade? I live in Park City, UT.

review.reviewBody: Hotel dorm style fridges are terrible.  I travel 11 months out of the year.  I wanted something reliable and proven.  I found Dometic and didn’t look further.  It keeps my steaks frozen solid and my eggs, butter and bacon at the  perfect temperature.  The set temperature is very stable and it has more than enough space for my groceries.
review.name: Perfect For Extended Hotel Stays & Camping

review.reviewBody:
I've owned the fridge for a year now. Had to send my first on in because the doors would not snap off without breaking the plastic.

I'm about to send this replacement back because it's performance is just horrible. I have one zone set to 0C, there's ice in one part of the compartment, liquid water in another corner, and stuff at the top is completely unfrozen. The compressor will run for over an hour straight, shut off for 5 minutes, then kick back. Times like these it almost never stops running.

There are also times where it doesn't seem to want to turn on. I'll lower the temperature by 10 degrees and get nothing from the compressor. Even hours later, as the actual temperature in the fridge continues to rise.

I also have issues when setting the temperatures, there's been nights where the noise from the compressor has kept me up to the point where I will raise the set temperature so that the compressor stops trying to cool, but it still does not shut off!
review.name: Wildly Inconsistent Performance

review.reviewBody: I love my new bag! It's really confortable and spacious. I love how versatile it is. The only downside is there's only three different compartiments, the main one, a smaller one on top and the removable pouch. For day to day use, it's not really an issue, but for weekend trips or hikes, some compression bags are going to be a must. I would still recommend it to anyone, it's a great backpack!

I bought this pack because i wanted a roll top and easy access to the items in the bottom. The roll top makes it easy to shrink/expand the pack according to what I have. 
Pack carries weight very well. 
I have 2 complaints.
1. The women's version does not have mesh shoulder pouches. I really wanted that. 
2. Shock cords would have done a much better job at holding poles as compared to the velcro. 
Great pack otherwise.
review.name: Great pack! Carries heavy weight well. Women's doesn't have shoulder pockets.

review.reviewBody: I used this bag as cabin baggage on a plane and the size is perfect. I like that I can go through the zipper on the top to have a 2nd access to my belongings. I like the basket system or the straps which take the bag off our back and which is less hot when worn for a long time. Several pockets at the waist including a waterproof pocket. Side pockets for water bottles accessible when carried on our back. I also like the rain cover integrated under the bag. Ideal for traveling by plane and traveling without a suitcase. However, I have not tried it on a hike. For this purpose, I don't think the zipper concept would be ideal and I would like more compartments instead of just one.
review.name: Hiking and carry-on

review.reviewBody: This is the worst backpack I have ever owned. The frame and shoulder straps are incredibly stiff, and I have a bruise on my collarbone for wearing it for just a couple hours. The phone pocket is very inconvenient. The chest strap doesn't go low enough. The frame OSFA option is an ineffective idea because my spine is only 16" and the backpack frame sticks out several inches above my neck which makes it hard to look up. I would not recommend this to anyone for any activity.
review.name: Horribly uncomfortable, terrible design

review.reviewBody: I finally retired my old 2004 Eddie Bauer day pack and upgraded to this Mammut Ducan Spine (Ladies model). Compared to my old pack and carrying the same gear, it feels light as a feather. With the way the frame flexes, it rides very well and is very comfortable after a long day of hiking. Has just the right features I was looking for in a day pack and materials are of very high quality.
review.name: Carries Very Well
